  "texts": [
    "In the context of digital ads, we study the implications of algorithmic regulations designed to enhance transparency and reduce the degree of ad targeting.",
    "Our analysis suggests that polarization, both among voters and in equilibrium party positions, responds to changes in digital awareness/literacy and the persuasiveness of ads.",
    "1 Related Literature.",
    "Our work is connected to three streams of literature, the first on social media, echo chambers, and filter bubbles; the second related to advertising in digital and non-digital settings; and the third about the politics of polarization.",
    "Although we build on the emerging empirical evidence in these areas, our contribution is theoretical and develops novel possible channels from the use of AI tools in social media and other platforms to voter and political party polarization."
